      <scopecontent id="aspace_55ae642c01cba673f47cf6e88c37d8ff">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection consists of approximately 1000 items in four boxes. It is a collection of the personal papers and papers collected by Albert Gabriel Feuillerat, 1874-1952, professor of French at Yale University from 1929-1943 and professor of English literature at various American and French universities prior to that time. The papers were the gift of the estate of Albert Gabriel Feuillerat in 1953.</p>
         <p>The collection is arranged in four groups as follows:</p>
         <p>1. Personal papers of Professor Feuillerat which consist chiefly of letters by and to him, newspaper clippings, printed articles, correspondence with the Yale University Library, notes and miscellaneous items.</p>
         <p>2. Material on Paul Bourget, 1852-1935, French novelist and critic and brother-in-law of Professor Feuillerat, which consists mainly of an unpublished and unfinished manuscript entitled <emph render="italic">Sans Dieu</emph>, ms copies of his theatrical chronicles published in <emph render="italic">Le Parlement,</emph> LETTERS TO Prof. Feuillerat concerning Bourget; and copies of letters with a few originals by Bourget.</p>
         <p>3. Letters from various persons to various persons, collected by Prof. Feuillerat, with number and dates indicated (list on following pages)</p>
         <p>4. Autographs and poems only, which are not included in the above groups, Barriére, Théodore, 1823-1877; Brulat, Paul, 1866-1925; Coppée Francois, 1842-1908; Du Boscage, <emph render="italic">marouis;</emph> Great; Manuel, Eugéne, 1823-1901; Pluvier, Edourard, 1821-De Pons.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_2a3e71d40f8d5371c5dfc40742a7df2a">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Albert G. Feuillerat: educator; born in Toulouse, France; B.A., Lycée of Toulouse, 1891; M.A., University of Toulouse, 1896; Docteur des Lettres, University of Paris; professor, University of Rennes, 1901-1927; visiting professor at Harvard, 1923-1924, Columbia, 1927-1928, Yale, 1928-1929; Sterling Professor of French, Yale, 1929-1943, professor emeritus, 1943-1952.</p>  
      </bioghist>
